
[1]promote

   PROMO'TE, v.t. [L. promotus, promoveo, to move forward; pro and moveo,
   to move.]

   1. To forward; to advance; to contribute to the growth, enlargement or
   excellence of any thing valuable, or to the increase of any thing evil;
   as, to promote learning, knowledge, virtue or religion; to promote the
   interest of commerce or agriculture; to promote the arts; to promote
   civilization or refinement; to promote the propagation of the gospel;
   to promote vice and disorder.

   2. To excite; as, to promote mutiny.

   3. To exalt; to elevate; to raise; to prefer in rank or honor.

   I will promote thee to very great honors. Num.22.

   Exalt her, and she shall promote thee. Prov.4.
